1
00:00:35,440 --> 00:00:40,400
Throngs of people outside still
waiting for the bride to appear.

2
00:00:40,435 --> 00:00:42,325
She's not in there. I can feel it.

3
00:00:42,360 --> 00:00:45,796
Any moment now, she should
be leaving the hotel.

4
00:00:57,560 --> 00:01:00,757
I overestimated her.
I thought she'd be more elusive.

5
00:01:08,440 --> 00:01:11,591
- I don't understand what's
happening. - What is going on here?

6
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:21,913
I don't think they want us to know
which one the real bride is.

7
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:12,040
The streets are full of brides,
the skies are full of brides,

8
00:02:12,075 --> 00:02:13,925
the press doesn't know
which way is up.

9
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:17,480
- I'm a genius. Still no sign
of Marco Ballani? - None.

10
00:02:17,515 --> 00:02:20,640
- Our intelligence says he's gone
skiing. - Now?

11
00:02:20,675 --> 00:02:22,153
Then we're good.

12
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:48,956
Hello?

13
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:56,680
You! What the hell
are you doing in there?

14
00:02:56,715 --> 00:02:58,445
I am the wedding photographer.

15
00:02:58,480 --> 00:03:00,285
Can I have the tall people
at the back?

16
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:04,040
- OK, buster, fun's over.
- How long have you been in there?

17
00:03:04,075 --> 00:03:06,793
Oh, my God. This is not soda.

18
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:09,717
I'm gonna kill you!

19
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:25,158
- You are ruining my life!
- I've ruined plenty of lives.

20
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:28,076
You're nothing special.

21
00:03:32,320 --> 00:03:34,045
You abscess!

22
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:39,313
When I do get married, you will not
even know what continent I'm on!

23
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:49,885
Marco Ballani, you golden Roman god!

24
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:53,480
I will not be defeated
by that disease of a man.

25
00:03:53,515 --> 00:03:56,631
We're gonna have to
disappear completely.

26
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:00,073
We can get married in outer space.

27
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:03,236
Or the lost underwater kingdom
of Atlantis?

28
00:04:03,720 --> 00:04:05,980
Outer space?
I don't think you can yet.

29
00:04:06,015 --> 00:04:08,240
Is that what your intelligence
tells you?

30
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:12,072
We're gonna have to go somewhere
crazy remote.

31
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:13,036
Hi, Mum.

32
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:18,156
Oh, no.

33
00:05:18,840 --> 00:05:22,310
- What's happened?
- Nothing. I'm fine.

34
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:31,592
- I'm fine. - Well, that's good.
Just so long as you're fine.

35
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:33,805
Are you going somewhere?

36
00:05:33,840 --> 00:05:35,910
I don't suppose you're
in the mood for a wedding?

37
00:05:38,080 --> 00:05:40,005
There is somebody out there for you,

38
00:05:40,040 --> 00:05:42,925
somebody sensitive and faithful
and kind.

39
00:05:42,960 --> 00:05:45,405
But you'll never meet him
if you're hiding here.

40
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:48,520
Good. I don't want to meet him.
He sounds like a twat.

41
00:05:48,555 --> 00:05:51,633
I'm like kryptonite to men.

42
00:05:51,668 --> 00:05:54,712
Kryptonite dipped in cellulite.

43
00:05:56,080 --> 00:06:00,080
So, what's new on Hegg?
Give me the headlines.

44
00:06:00,115 --> 00:06:02,405
One of Donald's sheep drowned.

45
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:04,874
They had to fish it out
with a curtain rail.

46
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:10,600
- Hello.
- Mild out, isn't it, Iseabail?

47
00:06:10,635 --> 00:06:13,085
It's this global warming.

48
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:17,720
- Katie's back.
- Are we late?

49
00:06:17,755 --> 00:06:20,518
Too late to marry him.

50
00:06:26,160 --> 00:06:27,798
Quick!

51
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:33,069
Sorry. No.

52
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:37,876
Hi, Angus.

53
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:44,072
You're too late, Katie Nic Aodh.
He's mine now!

54
00:06:46,120 --> 00:06:50,200
There's always the Oban tinker.
He'll be visiting come September.

55
00:06:50,235 --> 00:06:52,965
And he's keen to marry
on account of his leg.

56
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:57,039
I'll marry you, Katie.
How old will you be in eight years?

57
00:06:57,160 --> 00:07:01,472
- 40.
- Could have gone to 36.

58
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:13,600
- The return of the native.
- Hello, Laird.

59
00:07:13,635 --> 00:07:15,955
That was quite the entrance, Katie.

60
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:19,600
And continuing the theme
of my public humiliation,

61
00:07:19,635 --> 00:07:22,085
I may need my old job back.

62
00:07:22,120 --> 00:07:24,200
What happened
to your fancy Edinburgh job

63
00:07:24,235 --> 00:07:25,845
at the trouser catalogue?

64
00:07:25,880 --> 00:07:28,474
I ran out of ways to describe
pockets.

65
00:07:29,040 --> 00:07:31,085
If you don't mind me saying, Katie,

66
00:07:31,120 --> 00:07:34,000
you've always had such a terrible
taste in men.

67
00:07:34,035 --> 00:07:36,753
I know. I've gone man vegan.

68
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:39,960
They say after the first six years
you don't miss them any more.

69
00:07:39,995 --> 00:07:42,085
You've picked the right spot
to try it.

70
00:07:42,120 --> 00:07:46,910
There are no single men left
on Hegg, are there, after today?

71
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:50,073
Except for me, of course.

72
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:55,200
Perhaps you'll dance with me
later on.

73
00:07:55,235 --> 00:07:57,565
You'll not be forgetting Hegg law,
Laird.

74
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:02,560
- You must dance with us all.
Eldest to youngest. - Oh, yes.

75
00:08:02,595 --> 00:08:04,445
The dance of the dead.

76
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:09,554
Which means I should get to you
about 4:30 in the morning.

77
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:12,796
So,

78
00:08:13,040 --> 00:08:15,165
how long are you back for?

79
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:18,165
Well, actually,
I'm thinking of staying.

80
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:22,045
I thought you said nothing
ever happened here.

81
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:26,995
No. Well, nothing happening
is becoming more appealing.

82
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:32,680
So, this is all very grown-up.
You've a wife

83
00:08:32,715 --> 00:08:35,325
- and a beard.
- Well,

84
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:38,600
Muireen thinks differently
of beards than you.

85
00:08:38,635 --> 00:08:40,556
And marriage.

86
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:45,920
Look, I truly hope you'll be...

87
00:08:45,955 --> 00:08:47,876
Aye.

88
00:09:27,800 --> 00:09:30,485
Hegg: An Island History,

89
00:09:30,520 --> 00:09:33,200
The Definitive Guide.
By Katie Nic Aodh.

90
00:09:33,235 --> 00:09:35,111
£5 a copy. We split the proceeds.

91
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:39,160
A guidebook to here? Don't be mad.

92
00:09:39,195 --> 00:09:41,285
Come see our disused toilet

93
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:44,080
that may or may not be haunted
by the ghost of a drowned cow.

94
00:09:44,115 --> 00:09:47,965
You see? We need to channel
this raw, creative energy.

95
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,040
Else you're liable to get restless
and go wandering off again.

96
00:09:51,075 --> 00:09:53,192
Nobody's going to buy
a guidebook to Hegg.

97
00:09:53,227 --> 00:09:55,310
Unless it's cheaper
than our toilet paper.

98
00:09:58,440 --> 00:10:00,795
A marketing conference? Here?

99
00:10:01,680 --> 00:10:04,520
- The tide has turned.
- For the marketeers.

100
00:10:04,555 --> 00:10:07,637
£1 each
or £1.50 with hair.

101
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:13,525
They want my castle, just as it is,
for a week.

102
00:10:13,560 --> 00:10:16,393
- Good luck to them.
- This is a beautiful island, Katie.

103
00:10:17,480 --> 00:10:19,165
In a way...

104
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:22,920
New beginnings.
It's like the whale all over again.

105
00:10:22,955 --> 00:10:25,977
You're not too young
to remember the whale, Laird?

106
00:10:26,012 --> 00:10:29,000
- No, I remember.
- There'll be money in this lot too.

107
00:10:29,035 --> 00:10:31,965
No throwing yourself
at the men visitors, Katie.

108
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:36,312
We don't want them thinking this is
the Orkneys where anything goes.

109
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:38,720
Now, Katie, chop chop.
Chapter One,

110
00:10:38,755 --> 00:10:40,925
in which a young woman and her laird

111
00:10:40,960 --> 00:10:43,800
rescue their island from certain
doom by writing

112
00:10:43,835 --> 00:10:45,631
a brilliant guidebook.

113
00:10:54,720 --> 00:10:58,000
The island of Hegg
lies half-drowned and wind-battered,

114
00:10:58,035 --> 00:11:00,577
the furthermost drop
of the outermost spray

115
00:11:00,612 --> 00:11:03,120
of the curling wave
of the Outer Hebrides.

116
00:11:03,155 --> 00:11:05,525
It has a population of 75,

117
00:11:05,560 --> 00:11:07,835
a majority of whom are probably
about...

118
00:11:08,640 --> 00:11:11,996
75. Or even older.

119
00:11:14,360 --> 00:11:16,685
Though Hegg no doubt has
a certain charm,

120
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:19,525
it has never been a popular
stop on the tourist trail.

121
00:11:19,560 --> 00:11:23,716
Even the Vikings never showed
the slightest interest in us.

122
00:11:23,751 --> 00:11:27,872
But the islanders remain
a hardy and resourceful people.

123
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:32,232
All those under 50 are now married,
except one.

124
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:35,205
The island has one B&B

125
00:11:35,240 --> 00:11:39,005
which offers the traditional
Scottish breakfast of haggis,

126
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,360
sausage, chips and beans, or if
you're feeling more metropolitan,

127
00:11:42,395 --> 00:11:44,565
you can have the continental
breakfast,

128
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:47,797
a bread roll,
two Weetabix and a Snickers bar.

129
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:51,245
Have we got any Michelin stars
I can put up?

130
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:54,800
- Are you not cold? Can I get you
a coat? - I'll be fine.

131
00:11:54,835 --> 00:11:58,285
- As always. - You think?
- I'll be dying either way.

132
00:11:58,320 --> 00:12:01,600
I've got to get out of here, Katie.
I've never been anywhere.

133
00:12:01,635 --> 00:12:04,125
And I want to see the world,
overdose on daiquiris

134
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:09,154
and be thrown into a volcano.
But you need money for that.

135
00:12:09,280 --> 00:12:12,829
If they ask,
we had two stars but they fell off.

136
00:12:16,560 --> 00:12:19,720
Welcome to the Sunshine,
Hegg's only B&B.

137
00:12:19,755 --> 00:12:21,525
We have rooms available.

138
00:12:21,560 --> 00:12:24,560
- We're looking for the castle.
- We're marketing people.

139
00:12:24,595 --> 00:12:26,994
I'll take you there... for a tenner.

140
00:12:27,400 --> 00:12:29,365
Mum!

141
00:12:29,400 --> 00:12:31,311
I'll take you.

142
00:12:36,480 --> 00:12:38,948
Oh, my God.

143
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:41,437
Do you like it?

144
00:12:43,320 --> 00:12:46,073
It's spectacular.

145
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:52,955
And that was the last we any
of us saw of the Americans.

146
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:09,165
'The gilt work glistened proudly. '

147
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:14,228
'Time had in no way diminished
the splendours of this castle. '

148
00:13:14,440 --> 00:13:18,672
We're dead. Lara's expecting to walk
straight into his stupid book.

149
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:23,478
She's not gonna blame you, Steve.
She is a reasonable woman.

150
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:33,040
Get me an office, a landline,
steeplejacks, welders,

151
00:13:33,075 --> 00:13:36,165
£20,000 in cash,
50,000 gallons of water,

152
00:13:36,200 --> 00:13:40,120
the construction crew
from Bonnie Prince Charlie

153
00:13:40,155 --> 00:13:42,076
and a cappuccino.

154
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:01,965
A seal. Look. How cute.

155
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,560
I've no idea where we are,
but it's perfect.

156
00:14:05,595 --> 00:14:09,085
'The sea turns
and shakes its manacles of salt

157
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:12,960
at the sharp rocks
on which too many waves have died. '

158
00:14:12,995 --> 00:14:14,916
What's that?

159
00:14:15,040 --> 00:14:18,350
It's you.
Chapter 49 of my favourite book.

160
00:14:19,160 --> 00:14:22,994
- The Ornithologist's Wife.
- Really?

161
00:14:23,640 --> 00:14:28,589
My husband is gonna be one of the
great writers of the 21 st century.

162
00:14:29,560 --> 00:14:33,473
- So where are we exactly?
- You know where we are.

163
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:38,356
Do I?

164
00:14:58,040 --> 00:14:59,473
No!

165
00:15:10,040 --> 00:15:12,280
It's just how you described it.

166
00:15:12,315 --> 00:15:13,565
We're on Hegg.

167
00:15:13,600 --> 00:15:17,360
You don't remember it
from your many research trips?

168
00:15:17,395 --> 00:15:19,485
Hey, you guys.

169
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:22,600
I don't know why
we didn't think of this before.

170
00:15:22,635 --> 00:15:24,880
I'm sorry we can't have friends
and family.

171
00:15:24,915 --> 00:15:26,598
But this is so special, isn't it?

172
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:30,878
It's perfect. And it's just us.

173
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:35,513
Let's go in. I have to see the Hall
of a Million Feathers.

174
00:15:36,320 --> 00:15:40,996
- Should we? - Yes, you really
should. It's quite something.

175
00:16:03,960 --> 00:16:05,445
Do you like your room?

176
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:08,645
We had 40 master craftsmen working
through the night.

177
00:16:08,680 --> 00:16:12,760
- One of them was 80. - Why didn't
you just tell her I made it all up?

178
00:16:12,795 --> 00:16:15,280
When Lara wants to go
to the Big Rock Candy Mountain,

179
00:16:15,315 --> 00:16:16,765
I don't take her to Elm Street.

180
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:19,280
This is your first time on Hegg,
isn't it?

181
00:16:19,315 --> 00:16:20,845
You Googled the entire book.

182
00:16:20,880 --> 00:16:23,314
You're the first person
ever to have a problem with that.

183
00:16:26,080 --> 00:16:27,672
I need some air.

184
00:16:29,200 --> 00:16:32,560
There are only seven people
in the world who know we're here.

185
00:16:32,595 --> 00:16:35,974
Anybody asks,
you're at a marketing conference.

186
00:16:36,009 --> 00:16:39,353
Keep your head down,
and wear a hat, Tolstoy.

187
00:16:50,440 --> 00:16:53,280
If you can safely navigate
the many rabbit holes,

188
00:16:53,315 --> 00:16:55,685
Hegg can be a great place to ramble.

189
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:58,775
And as the islanders say,
if you don't like the weather here,

190
00:16:58,810 --> 00:17:01,830
just wait 20 minutes and maybe
you will. End of Chapter One.

191
00:17:08,720 --> 00:17:12,759
Chapter Two: Hegg's top hot spots.

192
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:18,640
The people of the island are rightly
proud of this ageing public amenity.

193
00:17:18,675 --> 00:17:23,240
The ornate urinals
are enamelled in peacock colours,

194
00:17:23,275 --> 00:17:27,074
while the cow-sized cubicle is...

195
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:31,394
genuinely frightening.

196
00:17:45,800 --> 00:17:47,756
Laird.

197
00:17:56,920 --> 00:18:00,959
Hello?
Pretty sure that's not a real cow.

198
00:18:01,600 --> 00:18:04,433
Unless it's got hold of a kazoo.

199
00:18:09,160 --> 00:18:11,885
- Sorry.
- Oh, no, no, really. I'm...

200
00:18:11,920 --> 00:18:13,640
The laird of the island has
a similar hat.

201
00:18:13,675 --> 00:18:15,000
Sorry to barge in on you, Mrs...

202
00:18:15,035 --> 00:18:18,285
- Not Mrs.
- No, no. No.

203
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:21,118
I was just pretending
to be the ghost of this cow,

204
00:18:21,320 --> 00:18:24,153
which, of course,
sounds completely mad.

205
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:27,956
Not at all.

206
00:18:28,360 --> 00:18:29,725
Sorry. From the outside,

207
00:18:29,760 --> 00:18:32,560
your home looks like it might
be open to the public.

208
00:18:32,595 --> 00:18:34,790
My home?

209
00:18:35,320 --> 00:18:38,120
You don't live here?

210
00:18:38,155 --> 00:18:40,885
Not in this toilet, no.

211
00:18:40,920 --> 00:18:44,360
Here we live in primitive dwellings
anthropologists like

212
00:18:44,395 --> 00:18:45,925
to call houses.

213
00:18:45,960 --> 00:18:51,353
Please forgive me. I've spent a lot
of time with... hermits.

214
00:18:52,160 --> 00:18:54,680
For someone in marketing,
you're not very good at lying.

215
00:18:54,715 --> 00:18:56,796
I'm still quite junior.

216
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:02,068
- Katie.
- I'm J...

217
00:19:04,480 --> 00:19:07,160
John. John... son. John...

218
00:19:07,195 --> 00:19:10,117
- John.
- John Johnson.

219
00:19:10,152 --> 00:19:13,005
And I'm... I'm quite lost.

220
00:19:13,040 --> 00:19:16,828
No wonder. That book isn't right
about anything.

221
00:19:18,480 --> 00:19:21,320
You haven't read it. No one's read
it, not all the way through.

222
00:19:21,355 --> 00:19:23,640
That's the only book ever written
about Hegg.

223
00:19:23,675 --> 00:19:25,565
Everybody who can read has read it.

224
00:19:25,600 --> 00:19:28,840
- The Hegg Book Club gave it four
out of ten. - Four out of ten?

225
00:19:28,875 --> 00:19:31,405
We thought it picked up
around page 600.

226
00:19:31,440 --> 00:19:34,200
The architecture of the book
was probably quite deliberate.

227
00:19:34,235 --> 00:19:36,525
Wow, the Hegg Book Club
are a tough crowd.

228
00:19:36,560 --> 00:19:40,600
Oh, and the love story?
I didn't buy that at all.

229
00:19:40,635 --> 00:19:42,685
It was just soulless.

230
00:19:42,720 --> 00:19:45,880
- Soulless? - Maybe his second
boo will be better.

231
00:19:45,915 --> 00:19:48,045
- Is it out yet?
- Not yet, no.

232
00:19:48,080 --> 00:19:51,125
God. It's been years.
Either he's very,

233
00:19:51,160 --> 00:19:55,080
very blocked or it's even longer
than that one. Can you imagine?

234
00:19:55,115 --> 00:19:58,709
Do you want me to carry it
for a bit?

235
00:20:01,440 --> 00:20:03,725
Oh, no, no, no. You want lona.

236
00:20:03,760 --> 00:20:06,840
There's no monastery here.
No monks. No miracles.

237
00:20:06,875 --> 00:20:09,885
- That's OK.
- But no free accommodation here.

238
00:20:09,920 --> 00:20:13,960
I believe in God so-so, but I'm also
very interested in yoga.

239
00:20:13,995 --> 00:20:17,800
- Hung jury, you see.
So no discount. - No problem.

240
00:20:17,835 --> 00:20:20,030
