- I'll throw another puffin on the
griddle for you. - No, thanks.

719
01:00:59,880 --> 01:01:03,077
Griddled puffin? On a Friday?

720
01:01:05,040 --> 01:01:09,520
Ah, our first home.
What a life we could have had.

721
01:01:09,555 --> 01:01:12,398
Yeah. Come on.

722
01:01:16,240 --> 01:01:20,360
So you think this Reverend McDonagh
can help untangle us?

723
01:01:20,395 --> 01:01:24,480
Well, I can't recall going to him
with a similar problem,

724
01:01:24,515 --> 01:01:26,436
but, yes, he'll know what to do.

725
01:01:27,720 --> 01:01:30,560
There's something about islands,
isn't there?

726
01:01:30,595 --> 01:01:32,357
Or is it just that I'm from one?

727
01:01:32,800 --> 01:01:36,759
- No, there's something about
islands. - And this is just Hegg.

728
01:01:36,920 --> 01:01:39,560
We're the plain Jane
of the Hebrides.

729
01:01:39,595 --> 01:01:42,774
You should see Barra. It's stunning.

730
01:01:42,809 --> 01:01:45,954
I like this one.
It's beautiful.

731
01:01:49,480 --> 01:01:51,869
I wish I'd come here sooner.

732
01:01:58,520 --> 01:02:00,715
- Stay away from her, Englishman!
- Angus!

733
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:05,600
- Mr April? - You come over here,
taking our women.

734
01:02:05,635 --> 01:02:08,239
Your women? Angus, don't!

735
01:02:10,040 --> 01:02:13,320
Run away with me. I never thought
I had a chance with you

736
01:02:13,355 --> 01:02:16,600
until you came back and then...
Marry me.

737
01:02:16,635 --> 01:02:20,285
You are married to Muireen.

738
01:02:20,320 --> 01:02:24,200
But I don't want her. I never wanted
her. I always wanted you.

739
01:02:24,235 --> 01:02:27,160
Shame. You're married,
she's married. Oh, what a tragedy.

740
01:02:27,195 --> 01:02:29,520
She's married? Who to?

741
01:02:29,555 --> 01:02:31,405
To me.

742
01:02:31,440 --> 01:02:33,396
Is that true?

743
01:02:36,600 --> 01:02:39,120
Right, then. I'll fight you for her.

744
01:02:39,155 --> 01:02:41,280
- No.
- No, no. I don't fight.

745
01:02:41,315 --> 01:02:43,080
I win. I get to keep her.

746
01:02:43,115 --> 01:02:45,036
Angus!

747
01:02:49,680 --> 01:02:53,800
I wanted to grow old with you.
You're beautiful and clever now.

748
01:02:53,835 --> 01:02:55,325
It's easy to love you now.

749
01:02:55,360 --> 01:02:58,240
But I'll still love you
when the wind's dried you out.

750
01:02:58,275 --> 01:03:01,710
And when you're old and broken.
Will he?

751
01:03:05,200 --> 01:03:09,120
Angus, I'm sorry.
Go back to Muireen.

752
01:03:09,155 --> 01:03:11,759
Sort it out. She loves you.

753
01:03:12,440 --> 01:03:15,273
It's better
when people love you back.

754
01:03:16,120 --> 01:03:18,076
So do you love him?

755
01:03:21,560 --> 01:03:23,869
- Come on.
- I'm all right here.

756
01:03:37,040 --> 01:03:39,445
Wow. It's just amazing.

757
01:03:39,480 --> 01:03:42,995
I used to come out here a lot,
on my own.

758
01:03:57,680 --> 01:04:01,720
Only married 5 minutes and already
chasing after another woman, eh?

759
01:04:01,755 --> 01:04:04,245
Why not give this marriage
a go first?

760
01:04:04,280 --> 01:04:08,239
Because the woman he's engaged
to is Lara Tyler.

761
01:04:09,840 --> 01:04:12,035
She's an actress.

762
01:04:13,600 --> 01:04:18,000
She's ultra beautiful,
mind-blowingly talented,

763
01:04:18,035 --> 01:04:22,445
and rare, and fine, and modest,

764
01:04:22,480 --> 01:04:26,840
and generous, and nice,
and brilliant at everything.

765
01:04:26,875 --> 01:04:30,257
- But he's married to you.
- Exactly.

766
01:04:30,292 --> 01:04:33,346
A mind-blowingly ordinary
shop assistant

767
01:04:33,381 --> 01:04:36,400
from the Outer Hebrides.
Bit of a comedown.

768
01:04:36,435 --> 01:04:38,356
You're not ordinary.

769
01:04:40,800 --> 01:04:43,440
She could be Miss Universe
with a Nobel Peace Prize

770
01:04:43,475 --> 01:04:46,876
and she'd still be wrong
for somebody.

771
01:04:47,040 --> 01:04:50,828
Weddings are like sunsets.
The romance of a moment.

772
01:04:52,240 --> 01:04:55,480
Marriage is the sea
into which that red sun sets.

773
01:04:55,515 --> 01:04:57,885
We got married by mistake.

774
01:04:57,920 --> 01:05:02,325
- Probably not the strongest basis
for an enduring marriage. - No.

775
01:05:02,360 --> 01:05:07,760
Then, in days past, the MacNeils of
Barra, huge ginger brutes they were,

776
01:05:07,795 --> 01:05:11,560
would cross the Minch to Hegg
to steal our sheep

777
01:05:11,595 --> 01:05:13,645
and snatch a wife at the same time.

778
01:05:13,680 --> 01:05:17,360
But if we could reclaim the woman
before consummation,

779
01:05:17,395 --> 01:05:21,005
the marriage didn't count.
It's still in Hegg law.

780
01:05:21,040 --> 01:05:23,880
So if we can make it
to Cathedral Cove before nightfall,

781
01:05:23,915 --> 01:05:27,394
your licence with Miss Tyler
would still be valid

782
01:05:27,429 --> 01:05:30,873
and the original ceremony
could go ahead as planned.

783
01:05:30,960 --> 01:05:34,032
If that's what you really want.

784
01:05:34,840 --> 01:05:37,205
How long have we got
before it gets dark?

785
01:05:37,240 --> 01:05:41,640
About half an hour. When God made
time, he made plenty of it.

786
01:05:41,675 --> 01:05:45,030
When God made twine,
he made balls of it.

787
01:05:47,800 --> 01:05:52,191
Well, you think about it
while I get my things ready.

788
01:05:52,320 --> 01:05:58,200
Oh, one last thing.
Has the marriage been consummated?

789
01:05:58,235 --> 01:06:02,432
- No.
- I just haven't had time.

790
01:06:04,600 --> 01:06:07,239
When God made time...

791
01:06:10,720 --> 01:06:12,598
Hello?

792
01:06:12,633 --> 01:06:14,476
Lara?

793
01:06:15,200 --> 01:06:17,156
James?

794
01:06:18,520 --> 01:06:22,672
- Why has she brought us here?
- What is this place?

795
01:06:31,080 --> 01:06:33,885
How do you know when
you've met 'the one'?

796
01:06:33,920 --> 01:06:36,480
Whenever you look at them,
you find yourself singing

797
01:06:36,515 --> 01:06:39,438
'You Are The Wind Beneath My Wings. '

798
01:06:41,600 --> 01:06:44,125
Is that what happens
when you're with Lara?

799
01:06:44,160 --> 01:06:47,816
They asked 10,000 men
to name their ideal partner

800
01:06:47,851 --> 01:06:51,472
and 9,800 said Lara.
Statistically that includes

801
01:06:51,720 --> 01:06:53,676
at least 800 gay men.

802
01:06:53,960 --> 01:06:57,920
If you're male and Lara Tyler's
interested in you, she's the one,

803
01:06:57,955 --> 01:06:59,876
it's kind of a rule.

804
01:07:01,080 --> 01:07:03,913
If you can't be happy
with Lara Tyler,

805
01:07:04,920 --> 01:07:07,480
you can't be happy with anyone.

806
01:07:14,160 --> 01:07:19,154
You are sure about this? Because you
seem like a good match to me.

807
01:07:32,080 --> 01:07:37,118
Do you, James Neil Arber,
take Katie Nic Aodh

808
01:07:37,153 --> 01:07:42,156
- as your lawful wedded wife?
- No, I do not.

809
01:07:42,600 --> 01:07:47,525
And do you, Katie Nic Aodh,
take James Neil Arber

810
01:07:47,560 --> 01:07:53,669
- as your lawful wedded husband?
- Absolutely not. No. Thank you.

811
01:07:55,400 --> 01:07:59,880
I would ask if you would now remove
and return your rings as a sign

812
01:07:59,915 --> 01:08:01,916
that you are not married.

813
01:08:22,840 --> 01:08:25,912
Follow soon. We need to hurry.

814
01:08:31,640 --> 01:08:34,791
Good thing there are no pets
involved.

815
01:08:36,400 --> 01:08:38,560
If I wasn't in the middle
of the Atlantic

816
01:08:38,595 --> 01:08:40,720
after one of the strangest days
of my life,

817
01:08:40,755 --> 01:08:42,676
I'd...

818
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,070
James, wait.

819
01:08:56,320 --> 01:08:59,357
If things don't work out
with Lara...

820
01:09:00,600 --> 01:09:03,068
I mean, she's perfect, obviously.

821
01:09:04,320 --> 01:09:07,205
But she gives you block.

822
01:09:07,240 --> 01:09:10,710
So maybe you're not one
of the 9,800.

823
01:09:11,200 --> 01:09:13,634
That's not so impossible, is it?

824
01:09:16,240 --> 01:09:19,949
Because then
you could not marry her.

825
01:09:21,160 --> 01:09:25,517
Then you could stay here.
With me.

826
01:09:49,800 --> 01:09:51,756
I know.

827
01:09:53,640 --> 01:09:57,110
This is where you tell me
I'm just one chapter,

828
01:09:57,520 --> 01:09:59,476
not a whole book.

829
01:10:12,600 --> 01:10:14,238
Go.

830
01:10:15,480 --> 01:10:17,357
Go.

831
01:10:28,280 --> 01:10:32,845
Guys! Lara's Tyler's not
in the castle.

832
01:10:32,880 --> 01:10:35,960
They're getting married
now in the haunted toilets.

833
01:10:35,995 --> 01:10:38,793
It's a local tradition. This way!

834
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:48,630
- You OK? - Yeah. You?
- Yeah.

835
01:10:50,280 --> 01:10:54,671
I don't really like big cat
documentaries.

836
01:10:56,680 --> 01:10:58,636
That's OK.

837
01:10:58,880 --> 01:11:01,155
If we're going to do this,
we'll have to be quick.

838
01:12:00,920 --> 01:12:05,277
Do you wanna taste the icing?
Do you wanna taste the icing?

839
01:12:08,600 --> 01:12:10,556
What is that?

840
01:12:10,960 --> 01:12:17,040
Now, sweetie, I may look like
a simple, cake-baking,

841
01:12:17,075 --> 01:12:21,033
small-town mom, but inside...

842
01:12:21,680 --> 01:12:25,195
I am a prize fighter,
and I will not rest while there

843
01:12:25,360 --> 01:12:29,000
is a single rod of depleted uranium
anywhere

844
01:12:29,035 --> 01:12:31,833
in South Carolina.

845
01:12:32,360 --> 01:12:37,480
Powerful stuff there. Lara Tyler
in 'Depleted', out on Friday.

846
01:12:37,640 --> 01:12:39,805
There had been rumours
of retirement.

847
01:12:39,840 --> 01:12:44,400
Last summer I was maybe thinking
of leading a more quiet life,

848
01:12:44,435 --> 01:12:46,356
but...

849
01:12:46,520 --> 01:12:49,080
then I met this amazing
Scottish woman.

850
01:12:49,115 --> 01:12:51,965
Terminally ill, never complained.

851
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:55,920
Actually, no, she did complain
about a lot of things.

852
01:12:55,955 --> 01:12:59,071
I heard recently
that she passed away.

853
01:12:59,600 --> 01:13:05,038
But I was able to help her fulfill
her dream to travel the world.

854
01:13:08,160 --> 01:13:10,116
Thank you, Lara.

855
01:13:50,160 --> 01:13:53,445
Hegg - An Island History,
Second Edition.

856
01:13:53,480 --> 01:13:57,360
The Hegg is the furthermost drop
of the outermost spray

857
01:13:57,395 --> 01:14:00,285
of the curling wave
of the Outer Hebrides.

858
01:14:00,320 --> 01:14:03,600
But for those curious enough
to take some time to discover her,

859
01:14:03,635 --> 01:14:07,565
Hegg's cliffs and moorlands,
meadows and sandy beaches

860
01:14:07,600 --> 01:14:11,991
reveal her to be an island ready
to exceed all expectations,

861
01:14:12,160 --> 01:14:14,805
a tiny rock of perfection

862
01:14:14,840 --> 01:14:18,389
jutting out of the restless
Hebridean Sea.

863
01:14:18,480 --> 01:14:22,553
This is James Arber's new book.
Much better, more mature.

864
01:14:22,680 --> 01:14:24,636
And only one chapter.

865
01:14:25,800 --> 01:14:28,245
Look. He dedicated it to Lara.

866
01:14:28,280 --> 01:14:32,560
Katie, but you're leaving again,
so soon.

867
01:14:32,595 --> 01:14:34,685
Guidebooks don't write themselves.

868
01:14:34,720 --> 01:14:37,965
But I'll never forget who gave me
my big break.

869
01:14:38,000 --> 01:14:41,497
I just came in to say hi and bye.
I'm on the four o'clock boat.

870
01:14:41,532 --> 01:14:44,994
I've got a flight out to New Delhi
and then onto Singapore.

871
01:14:45,320 --> 01:14:48,790
Harder to hit a moving target, eh?

872
01:14:49,600 --> 01:14:53,160
I should have known that bloody
guidebook would take off.

873
01:14:53,195 --> 01:14:55,116
Idiot.

874
01:14:56,000 --> 01:14:58,434
It's not the same without you,
Katie.

875
01:14:58,640 --> 01:15:02,758
Never was. We miss you.
I miss you.

876
01:15:03,000 --> 01:15:04,956
There Katie, that's for you.

877
01:15:05,320 --> 01:15:09,552
It's a bride.
For luck. It's the last one.

878
01:15:11,920 --> 01:15:14,445
- Thank you.
- That'll be £1.50.

879
01:15:14,480 --> 01:15:18,120
- You off again, then, Katie?
- I'm trying to.

880
01:15:18,155 --> 01:15:20,680
She'll be back.
Her dad was a traveller,

881
01:15:20,715 --> 01:15:23,877
but her mam was a 'stay-at-home'.

882
01:15:23,912 --> 01:15:27,039
No, I'm not sure she was, deep down.

883
01:15:27,200 --> 01:15:29,205
I really need to...

884
01:15:29,240 --> 01:15:31,196
I'll warrant you're a bit of both.

885
01:15:32,160 --> 01:15:34,116
Goodbye, all.

886
01:16:10,160 --> 01:16:12,116
Hallo!

887
01:16:13,480 --> 01:16:15,948
Hello! Hello.

888
01:16:19,480 --> 01:16:22,525
- Long time no see.
- Yeah.

889
01:16:22,560 --> 01:16:26,360
I was hoping for our first meeting
to be a bit more casual.

890
01:16:26,395 --> 01:16:29,125
What are you doing here?

891
01:16:29,160 --> 01:16:32,520
I've been trying to get your
attention with conventional weapons,

892
01:16:32,555 --> 01:16:35,405
- phones, emails, that sort of
thing. - I've been away.

893
01:16:35,440 --> 01:16:38,080
Yeah, and you're leaving again.
Did you not read my new book?

894
01:16:38,115 --> 01:16:43,165
- Not so much, no.
- You really should have read it.

895
01:16:43,200 --> 01:16:47,600
- The Hegg Book Club gave it seven
and a half. - Seven and a half?

896
01:16:47,635 --> 01:16:49,397
That's generous
for the Hegg Book Club.

897
01:16:49,432 --> 01:16:51,125
They said it picked
up around page six.

898
01:16:51,160 --> 01:16:55,520
- So you didn't see the dedication?
- It's dedicated to Lara.

899
01:16:55,555 --> 01:16:58,159
No! It's not!

900
01:16:59,880 --> 01:17:01,836
It's not!

901
01:17:07,280 --> 01:17:11,239
"To my wife.
A chapter can be a book. "

902
01:17:12,640 --> 01:17:16,633
- What does he mean, a chapter
can be a book? - I don't know.

903
01:17:20,480 --> 01:17:22,436
I don't know.

904
01:17:28,320 --> 01:17:30,038
Have you got a radio?

905
01:17:36,160 --> 01:17:39,574
He said to tell you,
the only person he ever wed was you.

906
01:17:39,609 --> 01:17:42,989
But he and Lara let the press think
they were married.

907
01:17:45,600 --> 01:17:47,556
He's not married?

908
01:17:52,120 --> 01:17:55,192
Katie, shall we go back?

909
01:17:59,560 --> 01:18:01,516
Would you mind?

910
01:18:16,840 --> 01:18:19,720
I can't believe you didn't read
my book.

911
01:18:19,755 --> 01:18:21,805
I couldn't really bring myself to.

912
01:18:21,840 --> 01:18:26,152
Well, I hope you will one day,
because there's a character in there

913
01:18:26,560 --> 01:18:28,994
kind of reminds me a lot of you.

914
01:18:30,480 --> 01:18:33,240
It's a book about a man,
a really stupid man,

915
01:18:33,275 --> 01:18:35,845
who makes a really bad decision,

916
01:18:35,880 --> 01:18:39,429
and how he loses somebody
amazing from his life.

917
01:18:41,120 --> 01:18:45,477
And how he comes to realise
he cannot continue in his life...

918
01:18:46,560 --> 01:18:48,516
without her.

919
01:18:52,320 --> 01:18:55,153
They say write about what you know.

920
01:18:56,680 --> 01:19:01,231
So, obviously, I set it against the
backdrop of the Spanish Civil War.

921
01:19:03,440 --> 01:19:07,005
- And Lara?
- She's absolutely fine.

922
01:19:07,040 --> 01:19:10,340
We agreed we weren't right
for each other.

923
01:19:10,375 --> 01:19:13,640
By the way, I read your
excellent guidebook.

924
01:19:13,675 --> 01:19:15,525
Really?

925
01:19:15,560 --> 01:19:19,800
How embarrassing. I've been quite
rude about you in the new edition.

926
01:19:19,835 --> 01:19:23,509
Well, I love intelligent feedback.

927
01:19:23,680 --> 01:19:26,620
And you're back
on Hegg now because?

928
01:19:26,655 --> 01:19:29,525
I'm on a sheep-stealing raid, yeah.

929
01:19:29,560 --> 01:19:34,190
I thought I might grab myself
a woman at the same time, but...

930
01:19:34,760 --> 01:19:39,629
Predominantly,
it's a sheep-snatching thing.

931
01:19:51,160 --> 01:19:53,116
Do you want me to sign that for you?

932
01:20:29,040 --> 01:20:30,996
Hey.

933
01:20:31,840 --> 01:20:33,796
Hi.

934
01:20:35,880 --> 01:20:37,836
I like this one.

